<![endif]-->  <p class="MsoNormal">Well, I made it through my first week as a Virtual Employee. After quite a few bumps and bruises I think we have 98% of the bugs out of the system. I have most of my system tools back and I have the office set up.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">We are still unpacking and trying to find everything AND trying to get everything fixed on the house that needs fixing. We still have to get/make a gate for the back yard so we can let the dog out. We still have to fix/replace almost all the doors in the house. We have to tape and mud my office, paint almost every room in the house. Finish out the floors. Get a garbage disposal. AND try to replace/fix everything that the movers broke or lost.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">With all of this please understand if I am not in a yuletide frame of mind. After “missing” Thanks giving since everything We own was on a truck and we ended up having dinner at IHOP. I have not found the Yule décor and with the cost of the move and the replacement of stuff and loosing 3 weeks pay for the move along with the outlook of supporting 3-6 people I cannot afford Yule gifts for anyone (even the kids) this year. <span style=""> </span>This has been a difficult month and the next few do not look much better. <span style=""> </span>And I know I will not be able to “go home” for any holidays for quite some time. My Grandfather passed away last week and I was not able to go to Texas for his funeral (neither were the kids). So over all it has not been a smooth transition and I’m not feeling very festive. <br /><br />Tori<br /> </p>

Ok, Well, We made it to TN.

Brrrrrr……

It is cold and we have seen what I consider snow …Jay just considers it light flurries.

I spent the weekend inspecting the house (which needs some work) and trying to help with the home improvement.

 

Grrrrrr….

The stress fracture is a common overuse injury seen in athletes and military recruits. Breithaupt originally described this injury in 1855. The injury is usually seen in the lower extremities, but it has also been reported in the upper extremities and the ribs. The most common locations for stress fractures include the tibia, metatarsals, fibula, and navicular bones. Less common locations include the femur, pelvis, and sacrum.
A stress fracture is caused by repetitive and submaximal loading of the bone, which eventually becomes fatigued and leads to a true fracture. The typical presentation is a complaint of increasing pain in the lower extremity during exercise or activity. The patient's history usually reveals a recent increase in either training volume or intensity.
The treatment of most stress fractures is relatively straightforward and includes decreased activity and immobilization; however, patients with some stress fractures, such as displaced femoral neck stress fractures and fifth metatarsal base stress fractures, are more likely to have complications such as nonunion.4,5 These complications should be monitored closely because surgical intervention may be necessary.

Wednesday, March 05, 2008

 

Over and out
Current mood: annoyed
Category: Life

 

Okay, so here's the deal: The Home Depot fired me last night. Their reasons are ambiguous and dubious, at best, but it's enough for them to decide that they're better off without me. The real reason, although they'd never admit it (for fear of being sued), is that I am going away to join the Army. Since I announced my intention to enlist on January 5th, I somehow managed to accrue 5 write-ups for various thinly-veiled offenses, all of them minor. I hadn't gotten a single write-up in the six months before that. Ergo: they were gunning for me the minute I made it clear that I was leaving.

This throws damn near all of my plans completely off. No vacation time to finalize my prep for Basic. No insurance to cover my family (and my daughter, who is about to have a baby). No money saved up to offset the time it'll take for the Army to start putting money in my account.

At this point I see no other option but to ship out for Basic very soon. We're talking, like, next week. I do, after all, have to ensure that my family is taken care of, especially Kathrine. On the first day I start Basic training my family will be covered under the Army's insurance. I'll miss Kathrine's delivery, I won't be there to make sure that she doesn't succumb to post-partum depression and I won't be able to take the time I want to say goodbye to my family and wrap up loose ends here before I go.

My wife, Tori, will hopefully post regular updates on what's going on with me while I'm away. I will be calling her as frequently as possible to make sure that she is well informed. If you have any questions or want contact information (PLEASE SEND ME LETTERS WHILE I'M AWAY!!!!), you will be able to get them here. Alternatively, you can contact her directly at the following email address:

tori.seals@gmail.com

I love you all and hope that all is going well in your lives. As I said above, please send me letters. Contact with the outside world while I'm away at Basic will be minimal. The more people who send me positive letters, even short ones, the easier it'll be for me to focus and maintain a positive attitude.

Peace be with you, Allah'u'abha and take care of yourselves!

 

Jay
